! Xmodmap is intentionally a no-op. Kept around so .xinitrc's
! `xmodmap $usermodmap` call doesn't error, and so the vcsh repo
! history (and the per-host -<hash> overrides) remain available.
!
! Why: keyd (/etc/keyd/default.conf) now owns the CapsLock remap
! at the kernel/uinput layer, well before X sees the key. It does:
!   capslock = overload(meta, escape)   (tap=Esc, hold=Super)
! That's strictly better than what this file used to do, and any
! Xmodmap rebinding of CapsLock here is dead code at best and
! actively conflicts with keyd at worst.
!
! Originally, this was:
!   keycode 66 = Control_L
!   clear Lock
!   add Control = Control_L
!
! On a machine without keyd, the CapsLock-as-Control swap is still
! the important behavior to preserve -- but Xmodmap is no longer
! the right tool. Xmodmap is X11-only legacy (doesn't work under
! Wayland) and has been superseded by xkb options for years. The
! modern, portable equivalent of the old swap above is:
!
!   setxkbmap -option ctrl:nocaps
!
! and every modern desktop exposes this as a checkbox somewhere:
!   GNOME: Settings -> Keyboard, or
!          gsettings set org.gnome.desktop.input-sources \
!            xkb-options "['ctrl:nocaps']"
!   KDE:   System Settings -> Input Devices -> Keyboard ->
!          Advanced -> "Caps Lock behavior"
!   Sway / Hyprland / wlroots: xkb_options = ctrl:nocaps
!   COSMIC: Settings -> Input Devices -> Keyboard -> "Caps Lock
!           Key". Writes xkb_options into
!             ~/.config/cosmic/com.system76.CosmicComp/v1/xkb_config
!           (same ctrl:nocaps option name; COSMIC is libxkbcommon
!           under the hood like other Wayland compositors.)
!   TTY/console: /etc/vconsole.conf or loadkeys
!
! So: prefer keyd if present (kernel-level, works everywhere
! including Wayland and TTYs); otherwise use the desktop's xkb
! option. Don't reach for Xmodmap.
